a framework for behavioral welfare analysis siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr centers programs projects education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home research at siepr research project a framework for behavioral welfare analysis title a framework for behavioral welfare analysis principal investigator b douglas bernheim dates march 1 2008 february 28 2011 sponsor national science foundation this project involves the development application and refinement of a unified framework for behavioral welfare economics the new framework is a natural extension of standard welfare economics in the sense that the standard framework emerges as a special case when choice anomalies are absent the standard approach to welfare analysis is based on choice not on utility preferences or other ethical criteria in its simplest form it instructs the social planner to respect the choices an individual would make for himself the guiding normative principle is an extension of the libertarian deference to freedom of choice which takes the view that it is better to give a person the thing he would choose for himself rather than something that someone else would choose for him stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
